Motorists, markets, business centres, schools, filling stations and banks were grounded in various parts of Imo State on Monday in compliance with the sit-at-home order by the Indigenous Peoples of Biafra(IPOB) Residents stayed indoors while roads, motor parks and relaxation centres were empty. But some desperate Okada riders were seen in some areas taking frustrated passengers to their various destinations at exorbitant fares.   Gunmen threaten more mayhem in Anambra     BREAKING: Peter Obi secures Labour Party presidential ticket     Gunmen abduct son, injure father in Abuja   Our correspondent, who monitored the situation, reports some drivers of the Imo City transport buses who braved the order operated through some bush parts to avoid the wrath of IPOB enforcers. In the Aboh Mbaise, Mbaitoli, Ikeduru, Owerri West, Ngor Okpala, and Njaba council areas, the picture was the same as markets and lock-up stores remained under lock and key. Those who came out opened only one part of their doors for safety. Some security men, including armed mobile policemen, patrolled major roads to maintain peace and order. Some of the commercial drivers who parked their vehicles lamented the situation had continued to bring hardship on their families.